    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Liberal for a Reason</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>James McGill letter disputes Jerry Nachman's August 13 Op-Ed article, which argues that majority of members of press covering presidential politics are liberals</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''On to Los Angeles, Still Leaning Left,'' by Jerry Nachman (Op-Ed, Aug. 13):</p>
        <p>If it is true that the majority of members of the news media are liberals, it should not surprise anyone.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''On to Los Angeles, Still Leaning Left,'' by Jerry Nachman (Op-Ed, Aug. 13):</p>
        <p>If it is true that the majority of members of the news media are liberals, it should not surprise anyone.</p>
        <p>Unlike average newspaper readers or television viewers, your average reporter is likely to know a few things that most of us don't, like who runs the local soup kitchen or the safe house for battered women, and how inadequate to their tasks each is. Or he knows the percentage of inmates in the local prison who are African-American. Or he sits in a courtroom and watches a wealthy defendant get house arrest for doing the same thing that a penniless guy got 10 years for yesterday.</p>
        <p>It may be that reporting on the human condition creates liberal reporters.</p>
        <p>JAMES MCGILL  St. Pete Beach, Fla., Aug. 15, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
